<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>break something down • break something up</xh5><p> <i>break something down—</i>1. destroy smth. by reducing to pieces: The old cars were <u>broken down</u> for their metal and parts. 2. cause smth. to be defeated; overcome smth.: The police tried to <u>break down</u> the prisoner’s opposition. 3. cause matter to undergo chemical change: Chemicals in the body <u>break down</u> our food into useful substances. 4. separate smth. into parts; refer smth. to different categories: The figures must be <u>broken down</u> into several lists.</p><p><i>break something up—</i>1. <i>(of ice, etc.)</i> cleave smth. into smaller pieces: Enviro Disposal Service can <u>break up</u> old concrete driveways, then haul away the debris. 2. disband an organization, etc.; cause smth. to cease: The king’s death at once <u>broke up</u> the unity of the Court.</p> </entry>
